Introduction to Classification and Regression Trees (CART)

Daniel Bauer

In this tutorial, we will introduce classification and regression trees. We will start with a basic simulated example with a single predictor that compares tress to (linear) regression. In particular, we will demonstrate when trees do well and when the don’t. Subsequently, we will revisit our three case studies, and check how trees perform in these instances.

As before, we introduce a few helpful functions that make our life below easier.

TPR <- function(y,yhat)  { sum(y==1 & yhat==1) / sum(yhat==1) }

Regression Trees

Review of Concepts and Maths

Trees

As we discussed in the lecture, trees successively split the domains of predictors into two areas (greater and smaller), so that the final tree can be thought of as a model with constant predictions in square partitions of the feature domain. Hence, in building a tree, we need to address two questions:

  1. How to come up with the splits that determine the square partitions?

  2. How to come up with the predictions for each of the square partitions?

The second task is straightforward: We simply take the average of all predictions in the current partition.

For 2., one relies on a greedy algorithm: For each node, we go over all possible variables and all possible split levels, and then choose the combination of variable and split level that mimizes the prediction error. However, note that the tree thus will generally not minimize the squared prediction error – finding such a partition is computationally/algorithmically infeasible…

Excursion: The Sigmoid Function

In generating our dataset we will use the so-called sigmoid function, which will be a key ingredient when we discuss neural networks. It has the advantage that depending on the choice of a parameter, it can mimic a highly linear or a highly non-linear relationship:

\[ \sigma_{\alpha}(x) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-\alpha\,x}} \]

sigmoid = function(x) {
  1 / (1 + exp(-x))
}
x <- seq(-5, 5, 0.01)
plot(x, sigmoid(x), col='blue')
lines(x, sigmoid(0.5 * x), col="red")
lines(x, sigmoid(5 * x), col="green")

So we notice that for a small choice of \(\alpha\) (red curve), we obtain a relationship that is almost linear (and, indeed, as \(\alpha\) becomes smaller and smaller, \(\sigma_{\alpha}\) approaches a perfectly linear function). Whereas for a larger choice of \(\alpha\) (green curve), we almost obtain a step function (and, indeed, as \(\alpha\) becomes larger and larger, \(\sigma_{\alpha}\) approaches a step function).

A Simulated Example with One Predictor

  1. Let’s start by generating two datasets based on the sigmoid function with different parameters taken from above. 

    set.seed(3)
x <- 3 * rnorm(150)
eps <- 0.25 * rnorm(150)

y_1 <- sigmoid(0.5 * x) + eps
y_2 <- sigmoid(5 * x) + eps

mydata1 <- data.frame(y_1,x)
mytraindata1 <- mydata1[1:100,]
mytestdata1 <- mydata1[101:150,]

plot(mydata1$x,mydata1$y_1)

    mydata2 <- data.frame(y_2,x)
mytraindata2 <- mydata2[1:100,]
mytestdata2 <- mydata2[101:150,]

plot(mydata2$x,mydata2$y_2)

  2. And, for comparison, let’s fit a linear regression model to both datasets and let’s evaluate the out-of-sample error. 

    lmfit1 <- lm(y_1 ~ x, mytraindata1)
yOLShat1 <- predict(lmfit1,mytestdata1)
OLS_OOS_MSE1 <- sum((mytestdata1$y_1 - yOLShat1)^2)/50
OLS_OOS_MSE1    
    [1] 0.06001665
    lmfit2 <- lm(y_2 ~ x, mytraindata2)
yOLShat2 <- predict(lmfit2,mytestdata2)
OLS_OOS_MSE2 <- sum((mytestdata2$y_2 - yOLShat2)^2)/50
OLS_OOS_MSE2 
    [1] 0.1083534

  3. Let’s fit a tree to the second dataset. 

    library(tree)
tree2 <- tree(y_2 ~ x, mytraindata2)
plot(tree2)
text(tree2,pretty=0)

  4. Let’s use cross validation to see what size is optimal, and let’s prune accordingly.

    cv.tree2 <- cv.tree(tree2, K = 5)
plot(cv.tree2$size, cv.tree2$dev, type='b')

    prunetree2 = prune.tree(tree2, best=2)
plot(prunetree2)
text(prunetree2, pretty=0)

    ytreehat2 <- predict(prunetree2, newdata = mytestdata2)
OLS_TREE_MSE2 <- sum((mytestdata2$y_2 - ytreehat2)^2)/50
OLS_TREE_MSE2 
    [1] 0.07057412

  5. Let’s redo for the first dataset.

    tree1 <- tree(y_1 ~ x, mytraindata1)
plot(tree1)
text(tree1, pretty=0)

    cv.tree1 <- cv.tree(tree1, K = 5)
plot(cv.tree1$size, cv.tree1$dev, type='b')

    prunetree1 <- prune.tree(tree1, best=4)
plot(prunetree1)
text(prunetree1, pretty=0)

    ytreehat1 <- predict(prunetree1, newdata = mytestdata1)
OLS_TREE_MSE1 <- sum((mytestdata1$y_1 - ytreehat1)^2)/50
OLS_TREE_MSE1 
    [1] 0.07369689

Hence, the tree performs very differently between the two datasets: For the second dataset, the tree provided a very simple (and understandable!) model of the data, and despite the simplicity the prediction accuracy improved relative to the linear regressions. For the first dataset, on the other hand, the tree is far more complex than the regression model (seven vs. two parameters) but still provides worse predictions.

Hence, overall, trees are well-suited for modeling non-linear relationships – which explains their relevance as the foundational structural element for more advanced learners.

Case Study I: Caravan Insurance Purchases

Let’s go back to the Caravan insurance data:

library(ISLR)
data(Caravan)
dat <- Caravan
dat$Purchase <- I(dat$Purchase=="Yes")*1
X <- scale(dat[,1:85])
tst <- 1:1000
X.trn <- X[-tst,]
X.tst <- X[tst,]
Y.trn <- dat[-tst,86]
Y.tst <- dat[tst,86]
train <- dat[-tst,]
test <- dat[tst,]

As a reminder, our GLM and GAM models did not get a single true-positive with a cutoff of 50% – essentially the predictions were all zero. We obtained an AUC of 0.7456 for the GAM. The knn classifier did somewhat OK, though it is not perfectlt comparable (we cannot obtain an AUC). In particul, for \(k=1\) we obtained 45 true classifications, and 10 were correct. So that makes for a true-postitive rate of roughly 18%.

Classification Tree

Let’s try a classification tree, with the caveat that we have to change the default parameters. The standard value of the so-called complexity parameter cp is insufficient to generate sufficient splits, because a split only happens if there is sufficient heterogeneity in the nodes. We set it to 0.001 but we can generate an even larger tree by a lower choice.

library(rpart)
form1 <- formula(Purchase~.)
t1 <- rpart(form1, data=train, cp=.001, method="class")
plot(t1,uniform=T,compress=T,margin=.05,branch=0.3)
text(t1, cex=.7, col="navy",use.n=TRUE)

So an immediate advantage of the tree is its interpretability. It’s immediatly evident how the tree arrives at predictions. We specified a complexity parameter of 0.001, but rpart (usually) automatically performs a cross validation. The so-called cptable in the fit contains the mean and standard deviation of the errors in the cross-validated prediction. These can be plotted via:

plotcp(t1)

CP <- printcp(t1)

According to the documentation, “a good choice of cp for pruning is often the leftmost value for which the mean lies below the horizontal line”. So let’s go with:

cp <- CP[,1][CP[,2] == 9]
cp
          2 
0.003460208

Let’s prune accordingly:

t2 <- prune(t1,cp=cp[1])
plot(t2,uniform=T,compress=T,margin=.05,branch=0.3)
text(t2, cex=.7, col="navy",use.n=TRUE)

yhat.t2 <- predict(t2, test, type="prob")[,2]
table(yhat.t2>0.5,Y.tst)

  TRUE    4   1

So at least we are getting one right.

Case Study II: Credit Card Defaults

Let’s go back to our second example:

mydata <- readRDS("my_UCICredit_data.rds")
set.seed(42)
index <- sort(sample(1:nrow(mydata),round(0.75*nrow(mydata))))
train <- mydata[index,]
test  <- mydata[-index,]

As a reminder, the AUC for the GAM was 0.7754 and the confusion table for a GLM with 50% cutoff was:

\[ \begin{array}{l c c} & \text{Y.tst} &&\\ \text{FALSE} & 5572 & 1033\\ \text{TRUE} & 272 & 623 \end{array} \]

Let’s fit a classification tree:

library(tree)
myc <- tree.control(nrow(train),minsize=5, mindev=0.0003)
t1 <- tree(default ~ .,  data=train, control = myc)
plot(t1)

As a side note, the choice of 15 is somewhat arbitrary given the cross-validation results, in part due to the low number of defaults (just classifying as “no” is not a bad learner from a misclassification perspective). If we have a clear sense of what the costs of different misclassifications are, we can prune accounting for that. More precisely, prune.misclass(t1, best = 15, loss = matrix(c(0,c1,c2,0), byrow=TRUE, nrow=2)) would prune assuming cost parameters for c1 and c2 for different misclassifications. Of course, this is also relevant in the previous case study.

So not really an improvement relative to our GAM model…

So to summarize:

  • CARTS have several nice properties. They deliver understandable predictions (tree form) and they map non-linear relationships well.

  • However, in the context of our applications, they were not very competitive.
